The deprecation warning you're seeing is because **AsyncTask was deprecated in Android API 30 (Android 11)**. The `execute()` method is deprecated as part of this change.

## Why AsyncTask was Deprecated:
- AsyncTask had several issues including memory leaks, missed context, and concurrency problems
- Modern Android development recommends using standard Java concurrency utilities

## Recommended Solutions:

### Option 1: Use ExecutorService (Recommended for Java)
Replace your AsyncTask with ExecutorService:

```java
// Add these imports
import java.util.concurrent.ExecutorService;
import java.util.concurrent.Executors;

// In your Activity or as a field
private ExecutorService executor = Executors.newSingleThreadExecutor();
private Handler handler = new Handler(Looper.getMainLooper());

// In your onClick method
btnUp.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        MainActivity.wifiModuleIp = "192.168.1.100";
        MainActivity.wifiModulePort = 22;
        MainActivity.CMD = "python /path/to/script.py";

        // Execute network operation in background thread
        executor.execute(new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                // Your network code here (what was in doInBackground)
                String result = performNetworkOperation();

                // Update UI on main thread
                handler.post(new Runnable() {
                    @Override
                    public void run() {
                        // Update UI here (what was in onPostExecute)
                    }
                });
            }
        });
    }
});

// Don't forget to shutdown in onDestroy
@Override
protected void onDestroy() {
    super.onDestroy();
    executor.shutdown();
}
```

### Option 2: Use Thread + Handler (Simple Alternative)
```java
btnUp.setOnClickListener(new View.OnClickListener() {
    @Override
    public void onClick(View v) {
        MainActivity.wifiModuleIp = "192.168.1.100";
        MainActivity.wifiModulePort = 22;
        MainActivity.CMD = "python /path/to/script.py";

        new Thread(new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                // Background work
                final String result = performNetworkOperation();

                // UI updates must run on main thread
                runOnUiThread(new Runnable() {
                    @Override
                    public void run() {
                        // Update UI
                    }
                });
            }
        }).start();
    }
});
```

### Option 3: Use Kotlin Coroutines (If using Kotlin)
```kotlin
btnUp.setOnClickListener {
    MainActivity.wifiModuleIp = "192.168.1.100"
    MainActivity.wifiModulePort = 22
    MainActivity.CMD = "python /path/to/script.py"

    lifecycleScope.launch(Dispatchers.IO) {
        // Background work
        val result = performNetworkOperation()

        withContext(Dispatchers.Main) {
            // UI updates
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Points:
- **Network operations** must still run on background threads
- **UI updates** must run on the main thread
- **ExecutorService** is the recommended Java replacement
- Remember to **cleanup resources** in `onDestroy()`

The ExecutorService approach gives you better control over thread management and avoids the issues that led to AsyncTask's deprecation.

